{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584561"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:50:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:50:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14725"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.62,0.14,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43654"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5178"},{"type":"tags","id":"5181"},{"type":"tags","id":"10292"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18152"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETricyclic antidepressants are an older class of antidepressant medications that remain in clinical use today.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of tricyclic antidepressants?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct stimulation of serotonin receptors","Inhibition of monoamine oxidase","Inhibition of noradrenaline and serotonin reuptake","Enhancement of gamma-aminobutyric acid transmission","Antagonism of dopamine receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETricyclic antidepressants primarily work by blocking the reuptake of neurotransmitters at nerve terminals. \u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of noradrenaline and serotonin reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E increases the availability of these neurotransmitters in the synaptic cleft.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of monoamine oxidase\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of a different class of antidepressants (monoamine oxidase inhibitors). \u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of serotonin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is not how tricyclics work - they affect neurotransmitter levels indirectly. \u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonism of dopamine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of antipsychotic medications. \u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancement of gamma-aminobutyric acid transmission\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with anxiolytic medications like benzodiazepines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETricyclic antidepressants also have significant anticholinergic effects which contribute to their side effect profile, including dry mouth, constipation, and urinary retention. At toxic doses, they can cause dangerous cardiac conduction abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tricyclic antidepressants block reuptake of noradrenaline and serotonin at nerve terminals.","Tricyclic antidepressants have significant anticholinergic side effects.","At a toxic dose, tricyclic antidepressants can cause cardiac conduction abnormalities."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: A